03690nam a22005295i 9780804772907DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047729077 a10.1515/97808047729072doi  a(DE-B1597)582034  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPR428.A8bB35 2010 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a820.9/0032211 aBaker, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Demand :bWriting for the Market in Early Modern England /cDavid Baker. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tPreface: Writing for the Long Run -- t1. Marvelously Altered -- t2. Thomas Nashe, Pierce Penilesse, and the Demon of Consumption -- t3. William Shakespeare’s Troilus and Cressida: Credit Risks -- t4. “Allegory of a China Shop”: Ben Jonson’s Entertainment at Britain’s Burse and Volpone -- t5. “Idleness is an appendix to nobility”: The Preface to Robert Burton’s The Anatomy of Melancholy -- tCoda: Butter Buyers -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn early modern England, while moralists railed against the theater as wasteful and depraved and inflation whittled away at the value of wages, people attended the theater in droves. On Demand draws on recent economic history and theory to account for this puzzling consumer behavior. He shows that during this period demand itself, with its massed acquisitive energies, transformed the English economy. Over the long sixteenth-century consumption burgeoned, though justifications for it lagged behind. People were in a curious predicament: they practiced consumption on a mass scale but had few acceptable reasons for doing so. In the literary marketplace, authors became adept at accommodating such contradictions fashioning works that spoke to self-divided consumers: Thomas Nashe castigated and satiated them at the same time . William Shakespeare satirized credit problems. Ben Jonson investigated the problems of global trade, and Robert Burton enlisted readers in a project of economic betterment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAuthors and readerszEnglandxHistory. 0aAuthorshipxEconomic aspectszEnglandxHistory. 0aBook industries and tradezEnglandxHistory. 0aBooks and readingzEnglandxHistory. 0aConsumption (Economics)zEnglandxHistory. 0aEconomics and literaturezEnglandxHistory. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804772907zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804772907423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804772907/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles